explanation:
Summary: OS_mv itself contains no for statement, but to determine MISRA compliance you must also inspect the behaviour of any called functions because "the behaviour of a for loop body includes the behaviour of any functions called within that statement." The following symbols are required and why:

- OS_rename: direct callee of OS_mv; its implementation may contain for-loops or call other routines that do — those loops must be checked for loop-counter usage and side effects.
- OS_cp: direct callee and file-copy implementation; file copy routines commonly contain loops (e.g., read/write loops). Need its source to verify any for-loops are well-formed and do not modify objects used in loop clauses.
- OS_remove: direct callee; its implementation may iterate over structures or call other functions with loops that must be analyzed.
- OS_SUCCESS: constant tested by OS_mv; include to understand control-flow and whether return values affect loop usage in callers/callees.
- int32: typedef of the return type used by OS_mv and its callees; include to ensure any loop-counter types and signedness considerations are known when analyzing loop counters.
- OS_TranslatePath: called by OS_rename and OS_remove; may itself contain loops or modify global/state used by loops in higher-level functions.
- OS_FileRename_Impl: underlying rename implementation (filesystem-specific) — likely to contain iteration/loops over filesystem structures; must be inspected for loop-counter and side-effect rules.
- OS_ObjectIdIterateActive: iterator utility likely implemented with loops; its behaviour could modify iterator state or other objects referenced by loop clauses.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: iterator/index helper — may modify or return indices used as loop counters; needed to determine whether loop counters are changed only in the permitted clause.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: iterator cleanup routine; include to see if it has side effects relevant to loop control or modifies objects used as counters.
- OS_FileRemove_Impl: filesystem-level remove implementation; may have loops and side effects that must be checked for MISRA compliance.
- OS_OpenCreate: used by OS_cp; opening/creation helpers may include loops or side-effecting behaviour called inside loop bodies in higher-level code.
- OS_read: low-level read used by OS_cp; read loops are common — need to inspect any for statements in its implementation and side effects on buffers/counters.
- OS_write: low-level write used by OS_cp; same rationale as OS_read.
- OS_close: used by OS_cp; include to see if any loop-related side effects occur in its implementation.
- OS_printf: used by OS_cp (logging) — if used inside a for loop in that function or the callee contains loops, its side effects matter for clause restrictions.
- OS_ObjectIdDefined: used by OS_cp; may be implemented with loops or modify object state referenced by loop clauses.

Note: UT_Stub_* test harness functions were omitted because they are test harness stubs; include them only if the analysis will examine unit-test-transformed builds where those stubs replace real implementations. The listed symbols are the minimal set needed to inspect all possible for-loops and their side effects reachable from OS_mv.
